14
00:02:10,797 --> 00:02:12,377
‐ I see the first
star, look, Dad!

15
00:02:12,466 --> 00:02:13,756
‐ That’s good, Rioko.

16
00:02:13,842 --> 00:02:15,432
Now I want you to
find that special star

17
00:02:15,510 --> 00:02:17,390
that shines inside yourself.

18
00:02:17,471 --> 00:02:18,471
‐ The what?

19
00:02:18,555 --> 00:02:20,135
‐ Everyone has a star inside,

20
00:02:20,223 --> 00:02:22,143
a special talent,
something you’re best at.

21
00:02:22,225 --> 00:02:24,635
The person who knows
what her special star is

22
00:02:24,728 --> 00:02:26,768
will have a life
filled with happiness.

23
00:02:31,985 --> 00:02:33,605
‐ What’s my star?

24
00:02:33,695 --> 00:02:34,985
What is it, Papa?

25
00:02:38,742 --> 00:02:42,122
(woman mumbles, groans)

26
00:02:43,580 --> 00:02:45,000
‐ Stupid memories.

27
00:02:46,333 --> 00:02:49,093
(whimsical music)

28
00:02:54,508 --> 00:02:55,338
‐ Be a star.

29
00:02:55,467 --> 00:02:56,177
Be a star.

30
00:02:56,259 --> 00:02:57,259
Be a star!

31
00:02:57,344 --> 00:02:58,434
Be a star!

32
00:02:58,512 --> 00:03:01,142
These stupid Be a Star
posters are everywhere.

33
00:03:01,223 --> 00:03:02,023
Hm?

34
00:03:02,099 --> 00:03:03,519
What’s going on here?

35
00:03:04,685 --> 00:03:06,985
‐ Oh yeah, a beauty contest.

36
00:03:08,814 --> 00:03:10,404
Heels and swimsuits.

37
00:03:10,524 --> 00:03:12,364
‐ Did you order all these
posters special delivery?

38
00:03:12,442 --> 00:03:15,282
‐ So are you two ladies
going to enter the contest?

39
00:03:15,362 --> 00:03:16,112
‐ Huh?

40
00:03:16,196 --> 00:03:18,196
‐ Just what is going on here?

41
00:03:18,281 --> 00:03:19,531
What are these?

42
00:03:19,658 --> 00:03:21,488
‐ Posters.

43
00:03:21,576 --> 00:03:21,986
‐ And what’s on them?

44
00:03:24,663 --> 00:03:25,873
‐ A girl.

45
00:03:25,997 --> 00:03:28,037
And the young lady
who wins the contest

46
00:03:28,166 --> 00:03:29,916
will also get a
recording contract!

47
00:03:30,043 --> 00:03:32,133
You could be an idol singer!

48
00:03:32,212 --> 00:03:33,462
‐ Oh!

49
00:03:33,547 --> 00:03:35,467
‐ So why wasn’t I told
about this beauty contest?

50
00:03:35,549 --> 00:03:37,009
I’m the captain.

51
00:03:37,092 --> 00:03:39,052
People are supposed to tell
me what happens on my ship.

52
00:03:39,177 --> 00:03:41,547
‐ Oh, but we’re
thinking beyond that.

53
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:43,010
‐ Huh?

54
00:03:43,098 --> 00:03:44,768
‐ The crew with the Nadesico
are mostly young people

55
00:03:44,891 --> 00:03:46,851
with long and promising futures.

56
00:03:46,935 --> 00:03:50,395
It’s only right we
should promote thought

57
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:52,980
on what they might do in
their post‐military careers.

58
00:03:53,066 --> 00:03:54,436
For when the war is over.

59
00:03:54,568 --> 00:03:56,238
‐ When the war is over?

60
00:03:56,319 --> 00:03:57,489
‐ Yes.

61
00:03:57,571 --> 00:04:00,241
There will come a time
when all this will be over.

62
00:04:00,323 --> 00:04:02,493
Our crew needs to
start thinking now

63
00:04:02,576 --> 00:04:04,616
about what they want to
do once there’s no need

64
00:04:04,745 --> 00:04:05,455
for soldiers.

65
00:04:05,579 --> 00:04:06,699
‐ That makes sense.

66
00:04:06,788 --> 00:04:08,368
It’s kind of like
that old saying that

67
00:04:08,457 --> 00:04:10,667
happiness won’t deliver a
package to your address.

68
00:04:10,751 --> 00:04:11,791
You have to go looking for it.

69
00:04:11,918 --> 00:04:13,248
In that case, I think
it’s a great idea!

70
00:04:13,336 --> 00:04:14,746
‐ Good, and I was thinking
of making the winner

71
00:04:14,880 --> 00:04:15,880
the captain of the Nadesico.

72
00:04:15,964 --> 00:04:18,344
‐ It’s so exciting,
maybe I’ll enter it too!

73
00:04:18,425 --> 00:04:19,725
Huh?

74
00:04:19,801 --> 00:04:22,761
‐ Oh, nothing, it was just a
silly little idea that I had.

75
00:04:22,846 --> 00:04:24,096
‐ That’s great.

76
00:04:24,222 --> 00:04:25,642
If pop stars can become
police chiefs and mayors

77
00:04:25,766 --> 00:04:27,976
for a day all the time,
then why can’t our winner

78
00:04:28,101 --> 00:04:29,851
get to be the captain for a day?

79
00:04:29,936 --> 00:04:31,266
What a wonderful gimmick.

80
00:04:31,354 --> 00:04:33,614
So to all of you
would‐be superstars

81
00:04:33,690 --> 00:04:34,860
that want to become idol singers

82
00:04:34,941 --> 00:04:35,941
after the war with
the Jovians is over,

83
00:04:36,067 --> 00:04:38,607
not to mention all
those space cadets

84
00:04:38,695 --> 00:04:40,605
who’d like to try being
the captain of the Nadesico

85
00:04:40,697 --> 00:04:42,947
for a day, enter the First
Star beauty contest now.

86
00:04:43,074 --> 00:04:44,784
‐ And the winner gets
to be the captain.

87
00:04:44,868 --> 00:04:46,038
Isn’t that amazing?

88
00:04:46,119 --> 00:04:47,499
Who do you think it will be?

89
00:04:47,621 --> 00:04:49,961
‐ I bet I could spy
out the new (mumbles)

90
00:04:51,958 --> 00:04:53,538
‐ Punning in Japanese now?

91
00:04:53,627 --> 00:04:55,247
‐ Yes, it’s a little dated.

92
00:04:55,337 --> 00:04:56,957
The Japanese word for
captain is the same

93
00:04:57,047 --> 00:04:58,417
as the old word for spy.

94
00:04:58,507 --> 00:05:00,587
‐ Who says this show
isn’t educational?

95
00:05:00,675 --> 00:05:01,545
‐ Who are you talking to?

96
00:05:01,635 --> 00:05:02,475
‐ The fourth wall.

97
00:05:05,764 --> 00:05:08,394
‐ So what are you gonna do
in the talent competition,

98
00:05:08,475 --> 00:05:09,105
Rioko?

99
00:05:09,184 --> 00:05:10,064
I’m gonna sing a song.

100
00:05:10,143 --> 00:05:11,393
‐ I’m not entering.

101
00:05:11,478 --> 00:05:12,688
‐ Huh, you’re not?

102
00:05:12,813 --> 00:05:13,903
But it’s a chance to be an
idol singer and get famous.

103
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:16,820
Come on, Rioko, everyone
else is entering,

104
00:05:16,900 --> 00:05:18,400
so why not you, too?

105
00:05:18,485 --> 00:05:19,365
‐ I don’t want to.

106
00:05:19,486 --> 00:05:20,646
(munching)

107
00:05:20,737 --> 00:05:25,157
‐ So tell me, then,
after this war is over...

108
00:05:25,283 --> 00:05:25,953
(slurps)

109
00:05:26,034 --> 00:05:27,834
...do you have plans?

110
00:05:27,953 --> 00:05:30,833
What are you going to do, huh?

111
00:05:30,914 --> 00:05:32,584
‐ Mm, not bad.

112
00:05:32,666 --> 00:05:33,826
(both whine)

113
00:05:33,959 --> 00:05:35,839
‐ It’s none of your business!

114
00:05:35,961 --> 00:05:37,171
‐ I bet I know what she wants.

115
00:05:37,254 --> 00:05:39,674
‐ And I bet I know
where she wants it.

116
00:05:40,674 --> 00:05:41,424
‐ Bug off!

117
00:05:41,508 --> 00:05:42,258
(pop music)

118
00:05:42,342 --> 00:05:46,142
(singing in foreign language)

119
00:05:53,103 --> 00:05:54,693
‐ Thank you very much.

120
00:05:54,771 --> 00:05:56,561
Well, man, what do you think?

121
00:05:56,690 --> 00:05:57,570
‐ Huh?

122
00:05:57,691 --> 00:05:58,981
(girls giggling)

123
00:05:59,067 --> 00:06:01,027
(excited crosstalk)

124
00:06:01,111 --> 00:06:02,201
‐ Wow, look at ’em go.

125
00:06:02,279 --> 00:06:05,069
Looks like pageant
fever’s catching on.

126
00:06:05,198 --> 00:06:07,738
‐ [Man] Everyone wants an
excuse to stop thinking

127
00:06:07,868 --> 00:06:09,038
about what’s been happening.

128
00:06:09,119 --> 00:06:11,039
Even if it’s just for a day.

129
00:06:12,539 --> 00:06:14,419
(beeps)

130
00:06:14,541 --> 00:06:16,001
‐ Yes, definitely.

131
00:06:16,084 --> 00:06:17,544
No, absolutely not.

132
00:06:17,627 --> 00:06:19,877
My god, what were you
thinking with that outfit?

133
00:06:20,005 --> 00:06:21,385
‐ How’s it coming, Prospector?

134
00:06:21,506 --> 00:06:24,626
You do understand how
important this is, don’t you?

135
00:06:24,718 --> 00:06:25,888
‐ Don’t worry, I understand.

136
00:06:25,969 --> 00:06:28,219
Ever since our little
breach of security

137
00:06:28,346 --> 00:06:29,256
there’s been a steady
surge of malcontentism.

138
00:06:29,389 --> 00:06:32,309
You’re looking for
someone who will leave

139
00:06:32,392 --> 00:06:34,232
the crew’s minds like
putty in your hands.

140
00:06:34,352 --> 00:06:36,562
‐ We’re counting
on you, Prospector.

141
00:06:36,646 --> 00:06:37,856
Don’t let us down.

142
00:06:37,939 --> 00:06:40,019
The Nadesico needs
a super idol captain

143
00:06:40,108 --> 00:06:41,398
to make them happy.

144
00:06:41,526 --> 00:06:43,066
Someone who will make
the crew so happy,

145
00:06:43,153 --> 00:06:46,783
happy, happy, they’ll
all forget all the...

146
00:06:47,991 --> 00:06:49,241
(sighs)

147
00:06:49,367 --> 00:06:52,157
‐ Even for us this is
sinking pretty low.

148
00:06:52,245 --> 00:06:53,695
‐ Mr. Prospector.

149
00:06:53,788 --> 00:06:55,118
‐ Oh!

150
00:06:55,248 --> 00:06:56,828
‐ There seems to be some
misinformation going around.

151
00:06:56,917 --> 00:06:58,877
People are thinking
this is a contest

152
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:00,130
for a new captain.

153
00:07:00,253 --> 00:07:02,003
‐ Oh, I still have
applicants to process.

154
00:07:02,088 --> 00:07:03,758
‐ Don’t you think it
would be a good idea

155
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:05,590
to clarify things for them?

156
00:07:05,717 --> 00:07:06,547
‐ What for?

157
00:07:06,635 --> 00:07:08,265
‐ Well, we don’t want
everyone to think

158
00:07:08,345 --> 00:07:09,555
that they’ll be the new captain

159
00:07:09,638 --> 00:07:11,218
instead of captain
for a day, do we?

160
00:07:11,306 --> 00:07:13,216
‐ Oh, there’s no
cause for alarm.

161
00:07:15,310 --> 00:07:17,520
Why, isn’t it obvious, Captain,

162
00:07:17,604 --> 00:07:19,614
with your dad’s lame
looks and intelligence,

163
00:07:19,731 --> 00:07:20,771
you’re a shoo‐in!

164
00:07:20,857 --> 00:07:22,477
You’ll win without a doubt.

165
00:07:22,609 --> 00:07:23,359
‐ Oh!

166
00:07:25,028 --> 00:07:26,778
‐ Ladies and gentlemen,

167
00:07:26,905 --> 00:07:29,745
welcome to the first Star of
the Nadesico Beauty Pageant

168
00:07:29,824 --> 00:07:32,954
and our search for the
next captain of tomorrow.

169
00:07:33,036 --> 00:07:35,156
Tonight’s stellar
assortment of beauties

170
00:07:35,288 --> 00:07:38,118
begins with Icaro Amano singing

171
00:07:38,249 --> 00:07:40,839
the opening theme for
Get Me (mumbles) 5!

172
00:07:40,961 --> 00:07:44,091
(singing in foreign language)

173
00:07:46,341 --> 00:07:48,591
‐ The battle to be the
next captain has begun.

174
00:07:48,677 --> 00:07:50,847
Together with our
audience, we will be

175
00:07:50,971 --> 00:07:52,351
watching this event very closely

176
00:07:52,472 --> 00:07:54,722
while analyzing the results
compared to the polls

177
00:07:54,808 --> 00:07:55,728
we took earlier today.

178
00:07:55,809 --> 00:07:57,439
Here now is my co‐commentator,

179
00:07:57,519 --> 00:07:59,939
former champion
playboy Nigari Okaski.

180
00:08:00,021 --> 00:08:01,191
‐ Nice to be here.

181
00:08:01,314 --> 00:08:03,944
But what’s that
about former playboy?

182
00:08:04,025 --> 00:08:05,485
‐ Um, Nigumi?

183
00:08:05,568 --> 00:08:08,028
What are you wearing
that nurse’s costume for?

184
00:08:08,154 --> 00:08:09,744
‐ Well, actually I’m
going to demonstrate

185
00:08:09,823 --> 00:08:11,823
how to give a vitamin injection

186
00:08:11,950 --> 00:08:12,990
for the talent competition.

187
00:08:13,076 --> 00:08:14,866
You’re giving somebody
a shot on stage?

188
00:08:14,995 --> 00:08:15,835
‐ That’s right.

189
00:08:15,912 --> 00:08:17,332
‐ Are you certified for that?

190
00:08:17,455 --> 00:08:19,495
‐ Now, don’t move, Mr, Kitcat.

191
00:08:19,582 --> 00:08:22,292
I think I just pierced
Mr. Kitcat’s lower lip.

192
